"idolatry":{
  word:"idolatry",
  plain:"The worship of anything other than the true God — image-worship and heart-worship alike.",
  deep:"Greek EIDOLOLATRIA (G1495, lit. 'image-service') — idolatry as cultic act AND as misplaced ultimate devotion. Paul calls greed itself 'idolatry' (Col 3:5; Eph 5:5) — what one trusts/loves most. Hebrew uses many words: ELILIM (H457, 'worthless ones,' Lev 19:4), GILLULIM (H1544, contemptuous: 'dung-pellets'), PESEL (H6459, carved image), ASHERAH (H842, pole). The first two commandments forbid idolatry (Ex 20:3-6).",
  misunderstood:"Modern readers assume idolatry is only ancient image-worship. Scripture extends it to anything functioning as god in the heart — money, status, sex, self.",
  matters:"Idolatry is the root sin (Rom 1:21-25) and the persistent issue of OT history.",
  originals:[
    {lang:"Greek",word:"εἰδωλολατρία",translit:"eidololatria",strongs:"G1495",note:"Idolatry — image-service."},
    {lang:"Greek",word:"εἴδωλον",translit:"eidolon",strongs:"G1497",note:"Idol."},
    {lang:"Hebrew",word:"גִּלּוּלִים",translit:"gillulim",strongs:"H1544",note:"Contemptuous term for idols ('dung-pellets')."},
    {lang:"Hebrew",word:"פֶּסֶל",translit:"pesel",strongs:"H6459",note:"Graven/carved image."}
  ],
  rangeOfMeaning:["cultic image-worship","household-gods","greed-as-idolatry","ultimate trust in created things"],
  notMean:"Not only literal statues. Anything ultimately trusted instead of God.",
  cultural:"Israel's surrounding nations were saturated with images — Egypt, Canaan, Babylon. The exile was God's judgment for Israel's idolatry (2 Kings 17).",
  kingdomSignificance:"Idolaters do not inherit the kingdom (1 Cor 6:9-10; Gal 5:20-21; Eph 5:5; Rev 21:8; 22:15).",
  relatedVerses:["Exodus 20:3-6","Exodus 32","Leviticus 19:4","Deuteronomy 4:15-31","1 Kings 18","2 Kings 17","Psalm 115","Isaiah 44:9-20","Jeremiah 10","Romans 1:18-25","1 Corinthians 6:9","1 Corinthians 10:14-22","Galatians 5:20","Ephesians 5:5","Colossians 3:5","1 John 5:21"],
  relatedWords:["abomination","graven image","Asherah","Baal","covetousness"],
  category:"worship / temple / sin",
  sources:["Strong's H1544","Strong's H6459","Strong's G1495","Strong's G1497","Thayer's","BDB"],
  confidence:"direct-source"
},
"covetousness":{
  word:"covetousness",
  plain:"Greedy desire for what is not yours — and the worship of having more.",
  deep:"Greek PLEONEXIA (G4124) — literally 'wanting more,' greed. Paul names it idolatry (Col 3:5; Eph 5:5). Hebrew CHAMAD (H2530) — to desire intensely, covet — is the tenth-commandment verb (Ex 20:17). Covetousness is the engine behind theft, fraud, oppression, and unjust commerce throughout Scripture.",
  misunderstood:"Modern culture celebrates 'wanting more' as ambition. Scripture identifies it as idolatry when desire takes the place of God.",
  matters:"Tenth-commandment sin — the one that exposed Paul's own heart (Rom 7:7-8). The fountain of many other sins.",
  originals:[
    {lang:"Greek",word:"πλεονεξία",translit:"pleonexia",strongs:"G4124",note:"Greed, covetousness."},
    {lang:"Hebrew",word:"חָמַד",translit:"chamad",strongs:"H2530",note:"To desire, covet."}
  ],
  rangeOfMeaning:["greed","insatiable desire for more","envy","idolatry of possession"],
  notMean:"Not all ambition. Not the desire to provide for one's household.",
  cultural:"ANE legal codes also condemned covetousness as the root of theft and oppression. The tenth commandment is unique in addressing motive, not merely act.",
  kingdomSignificance:"Covetous = idolaters → no inheritance in the kingdom (Eph 5:5).",
  relatedVerses:["Exodus 20:17","Joshua 7 (Achan)","Proverbs 28:25","Luke 12:13-21","Romans 1:29","Romans 7:7-8","1 Corinthians 5:11","1 Corinthians 6:10","Ephesians 5:3-5","Colossians 3:5","1 Timothy 6:9-10","Hebrews 13:5"],
  relatedWords:["greed","envy","idolatry","theft","mammon"],
  category:"moral conduct / sin",
  sources:["Strong's H2530","Strong's G4124","Thayer's","BDB"],
  confidence:"direct-source"
},
"drunkenness":{
  word:"drunkenness",
  plain:"Loss of self-control through alcohol (or analog) — habitual or episodic.",
  deep:"Greek METHE (G3178) — drunkenness; METHYO / METHYSKO (G3182/G3184) — to be drunk. Scripture distinguishes use of wine (gift, Ps 104:15; medicinal, 1 Tim 5:23) from drunkenness (sin, Rom 13:13; Eph 5:18; Gal 5:21). 'Be not drunk with wine, wherein is excess (asotia); but be filled with the Spirit' (Eph 5:18) — the contrast is two different rules of life.",
  misunderstood:"Two errors: total prohibition (which Scripture does not impose, John 2; 1 Tim 5:23) and casual license (which Scripture forbids, Eph 5:18).",
  matters:"Drunkenness destroys families, communities, and inheritance in the kingdom (Gal 5:21; 1 Cor 6:10).",
  originals:[
    {lang:"Greek",word:"μέθη",translit:"methe",strongs:"G3178",note:"Drunkenness."},
    {lang:"Greek",word:"μεθύσκω",translit:"methysko",strongs:"G3182",note:"To become drunk."},
    {lang:"Hebrew",word:"שִׁכָּרוֹן",translit:"shikkaron",strongs:"H7943",note:"Drunkenness."}
  ],
  rangeOfMeaning:["drunken excess","habitual intoxication","loss of self-control"],
  notMean:"Not the use of wine per se in OT and NT contexts.",
  cultural:"ANE/Greco-Roman culture had widespread wine use. Drunkenness was common at festivals; the NT calls believers out of drunken excess (1 Pet 4:3-4).",
  kingdomSignificance:"Drunkards do not inherit the kingdom (1 Cor 6:10; Gal 5:21).",
  relatedVerses:["Genesis 9:20-27","Proverbs 20:1","Proverbs 23:29-35","Isaiah 5:11","Luke 21:34","Romans 13:13","1 Corinthians 5:11","1 Corinthians 6:10","Galatians 5:21","Ephesians 5:18","1 Peter 4:3"],
  relatedWords:["wine","sobriety","temperance","self-control","reveling"],
  category:"moral conduct",
  sources:["Strong's H7943","Strong's G3178","Strong's G3182","Thayer's","BDB"],
  confidence:"direct-source"
},
"reveling":{
  word:"reveling",
  plain:"Boisterous, drunken partying — wild celebration tied to excess.",
  deep:"Greek KOMOS (G2970) — revel, carouse, drunken party. Listed with drunkenness in vice lists (Rom 13:13; Gal 5:21; 1 Pet 4:3). In Greco-Roman culture KOMOS was specifically the post-banquet drunken procession in honor of Dionysus.",
  misunderstood:"Modern celebration ('partying') often obscures the specific picture Scripture names: drunken, lust-fueled public excess.",
  matters:"Listed with works of the flesh that forfeit kingdom inheritance (Gal 5:21).",
  originals:[
    {lang:"Greek",word:"κῶμος",translit:"komos",strongs:"G2970",note:"Revel, carouse, drunken procession."}
  ],
  rangeOfMeaning:["drunken festival","public riot","sensual partying"],
  notMean:"Not all celebration. Not joyful feasting under God.",
  cultural:"Dionysian and Bacchic processions in the Greco-Roman world were the public face of komos. NT believers were called out of them.",
  kingdomSignificance:"Forfeits kingdom inheritance (Gal 5:21).",
  relatedVerses:["Romans 13:13","Galatians 5:21","1 Peter 4:3"],
  relatedWords:["drunkenness","debauchery","lasciviousness","riot"],
  category:"moral conduct",
  sources:["Strong's G2970","Thayer's"],
  confidence:"direct-source"
},
